abstract.p:
Cosmic-ray (CR) anti-nuclei are often considered important observables for indirect dark matter (DM) detection at low kinetic energies, below GeV per nucleon. Since the primary CR fluxes drop quickly towards high energies, the secondary anti-nuclei in CR are expected to be significantly suppressed in high energy regions (
                  \begin{document}$\gtrsim 100$\end{document}
                GeV per nucleon). If DM particles are heavy, the annihilation productions of DM can be highly boosted, and thus the fluxes of anti-nuclei produced by DM annihilation may exceed the secondary background at high energies, which opens a high energy window for indirect DM detection. We investigate the possibility of detecting heavy DM particles which annihilate into high energy anti-nuclei. We use the Monte Carlo generators PYTHIA, EPOS-LHC and DPMJET and the coalescence model to simulate the production of anti-nuclei, and constrain the DM annihilation cross-sections by using the AMS-02 and HAWC antiproton data and the HESS galactic center 
                  \begin{document}$ \gamma $\end{document}
               -ray data. We find that the conclusion depends on the choice of DM density profiles. For the “Cored” type profile with a DM particle mass 
                  \begin{document}$\gtrsim 10$\end{document}
                TeV, the contributions from DM annihilation can exceed the secondary background in high energy regions, which opens the high energy window, while for the “Cuspy” type profile, the excess disappears.

sec.p:
CR heavy anti-nuclei such as antideuterium (
               \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
            ) and antihelium-3 (
               \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
            ) are postulated to be important probes for DM [16-18]. The 
               \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
             and 
               \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
             in CR can be generated as secondary productions by collisions between primary CR particles and interstellar gas, or they can be produced by DM annihilation or decay. However, the secondary 
               \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
             and 
               \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
             are boosted to high kinetic energies because of the high production threshold in 
               \begin{document}$ pp $\end{document}
            -collisions (17
               \begin{document}$ m_{p} $\end{document}
             for 
               \begin{document}$ \overline{ \rm{D}} $\end{document}
             and 31
               \begin{document}$ m_{p} $\end{document}
             for 
               \begin{document}$ ^{3}\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
            , where 
               \begin{document}$ m_{p} $\end{document}
             is the proton mass), and thus the signal from DM can be distinguished in low energy regions (below GeV per nucleon). Although the fluxes of anti-nuclei decrease rapidly with the increase of the atomic mass number A, the high signal-to-background ratio at low energies and experiments with high sensitivities (such as AMS-02 [19, 20] and GAPS [21]) make it possible to distinguish the contributions from DM interactions. Furthermore, an advantage for considering 
               \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
             and 
               \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
             is that their productions are highly correlated with CR antiprotons, so the uncertainties of the 
               \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
             and 
               \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
             fluxes can be greatly reduced by the CR 
               \begin{document}$ \bar{p} $\end{document}
             data [22].

In the literature (for a recent review, see Ref. [23]), the analysis of the DM-produced 
               \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
             and 
               \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
             are focused on the low kinetic energy regions, which we refer to as the low energy window. In our previous analysis [22], we studied the prospects of detecting DM through low energy antihelium. We systematically analysed the uncertainties from propagation models, DM density profiles and MC generators, and reduced the uncertainties by constraining the DM annihilation cross-sections with the AMS-02 
               \begin{document}$ \bar{p}/p $\end{document}
             data. However, the low energy window suffers from the uncertainties of solar activity (solar modulations). In this work, we investigate the possibility of probing DM with high energy CR 
               \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
             and 
               \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
             particles. In high energy regions (typically above 100 GeV per nucleon), the flux of primary CR particles drops quickly (the flux of CR proton is proportional to 
               \begin{document}$ E^{-2.75} $\end{document}
            ), which leads to a suppression of the high energy secondary CR particles. As a result, the fluxes of anti-nuclei produced by DM annihilation may exceed the secondary background and open a high energy window for probing DM.

We use the Monte Carlo (MC) event generators PYTHIA 8.2 [24, 25], EPOS-LHC [26, 27] and DPMJET-III [28] to fit the coalescence momenta for anti-nuclei with experiments including ALEPH [29], CERN ISR [30] and ALICE [31], and generate the energy spectra of anti-nuclei. The propagation of CR particles is calculated using the GALPROP code. We use the AMS-02 [11] and HAWC 
               \begin{document}$ \bar{p}/p $\end{document}
             data [32] and the HESS galactic center (GC) 
               \begin{document}$ \gamma $\end{document}
            -ray data [33, 34] to constrain the DM annihilation cross-sections. We find that the conclusion depends on the choice of DM density profiles. For a large DM mass (
               \begin{document}$ \gtrsim 10 $\end{document}
             TeV) with the relatively flat “Cored” type DM profile, the high energy window exists, while for a typical steep DM profile like the “Cuspy” type, the high energy window closes.

This paper is organized as follows. In Section II, we briefly review the coalescence model and determine the coalescence momenta for anti-nuclei by fitting the ALEPH, ALICE and CERN-ISR data. In Section III, we review the theory of CR propagation. In Section IV, we constrain the DM annihilation cross-section by using the 
               \begin{document}$ \bar{p}/p $\end{document}
             data from AMS-02 and HAWC and 
               \begin{document}$ \gamma $\end{document}
            -ray data from HESS. The fluxes of 
               \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
             and 
               \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
             for direct DM annihilation and annihilation through mediator channels are presented in Section V. The conclusions are summarized in Section VI.

The formation of anti-nuclei can be described by the coalescence model [35-37], which uses a single parameter, the coalescence momentum 
               \begin{document}$ p_0^{ \bar{{A}}} $\end{document}
            , to quantify the probability of anti-nucleons merging into an anti-nucleus 
               \begin{document}$ \bar{{A}} $\end{document}
            . The basic idea of this model is that anti-nucleons combine into an anti-nucleus if the relative four-momenta of a proper set of nucleons is less than the coalescence momentum. For example, the coalescence criterion for 
               \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
             is written as:

where 
               \begin{document}$ k_{\bar{p}} $\end{document}
             and 
               \begin{document}$ k_{\bar{n}} $\end{document}
             are the four-momenta of the antiproton and antineutron respectively, and 
               \begin{document}$ p_0^{\bar{  \mathrm{D}}} $\end{document}
             is the coalescence momentum of 
               \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
            . If we assume that the momentum distributions of the 
               \begin{document}$ \bar{p} $\end{document}
             and 
               \begin{document}$ \bar{n} $\end{document}
             in one collision event are uncorrelated and isotropic, the spectrum of 
               \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
             can be derived by the phase-space analysis:

where 
               \begin{document}$ \gamma_{\bar{  \mathrm{D}}, \bar p, \bar n} $\end{document}
             are the Lorentz factors, and 
               \begin{document}$ \vec{k}_{\bar p}\approx \vec{k}_{\bar n}\approx \vec{k}_{\bar{  \mathrm{D}}}/2 $\end{document}
            .

For 
               \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
            , we adopt the same coalescence criterion as in our previous analysis [22]. We compose a triangle using the norms of the three relative four-momenta 
               \begin{document}$  l_1 = ||k_1-k_2||,\; \;  l_2 = ||k_2-k_3|| $\end{document}
             and 
               \begin{document}$  l_3 = ||k_1-k_3|| $\end{document}
            , where 
               \begin{document}$ k_1, k_2, k_3 $\end{document}
             are the four-momenta of the three anti-nucleons respectively. Then, making a circle with minimal diameter to envelop the triangle, if the diameter of this circle is smaller than 
               \begin{document}$  p_0^{ \overline{\mathrm{He}}} $\end{document}
            , an 
               \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
             is generated. If the triangle is acute, the minimal circle is just the circumcircle of this triangle, and the coalescence criterion can be expressed as follows:

Otherwise, the minimal diameter is equal to the longest side of the triangle, and the criterion can be simply written as 
               \begin{document}$ \text{max}\{l_1,l_2,l_3\} < p_0^{    \overline{\mathrm{He}}} $\end{document}
            . See Ref. [22] for more details.

We use the MC generators PYTHIA 8.2, EPOS-LHC and DPMJET-III to simulate the hadronization after the DM annihilations and 
               \begin{document}$ pp- $\end{document}
            collisions, then use the coalescence model to produce anti-nuclei from the final state 
               \begin{document}$ \bar{p} $\end{document}
             or 
               \begin{document}$ \bar{n} $\end{document}
            . The spatial distance between each pair of anti-nucleons also needs to be considered, because the anti-nucleons should be close enough to undergo nuclear reactions then merge into anti-nuclei. We set all the particles with lifetime 
               \begin{document}$ \tau \gtrsim 2\,\, \mathrm{fm}/c $\end{document}
             to be stable, to ensure that every pair of anti-nucleons is located within a short enough distance [17], where 2 fm is approximately the size of the 
               \begin{document}$ ^3\overline{ \rm{He}} $\end{document}
             nucleus.

The values of the coalescence momenta should be determined by the experimental data, which are often released in the form of coalescence parameters 
               \begin{document}$ B_A $\end{document}
            . The definition of the coalescence parameter 
               \begin{document}$ B_A $\end{document}
             is expressed by the formula:

where 
               \begin{document}$ A = Z+N $\end{document}
             is the mass number of the nucleus, and Z and N are the proton number and the neutron number respectively. Under the assumption that the momentum distributions of the 
               \begin{document}$ \bar{p} $\end{document}
             and 
               \begin{document}$ \bar{n} $\end{document}
             are uncorrelated and isotropic, the relation 
               \begin{document}$ B_A\propto p_0^{3(A-1)} $\end{document}
             is expected by comparing Eq.  (2) and Eq.  (4). However, the jet structure and the correlation between 
               \begin{document}$ \bar{p} $\end{document}
             and 
               \begin{document}$ \bar{n} $\end{document}
             play important roles in the formation of anti-nuclei. So we derive the coalescence momenta by using the MC generators to fit the experimental data, and thus the effect of jet structures and correlations are included.

To derive the coalescence momentum of 
               \begin{document}$ \overline{\mathrm{D}} $\end{document}
             in 
               \begin{document}$ pp $\end{document}
             collisions, we follow the procedures described in Ref. [22] to fit the coalescence parameter 
               \begin{document}$ B_2 $\end{document}
             data from the ALICE-7 TeV, 2.76 TeV, 900 GeV [31] and ISR-53 GeV [30] experiments. We use MC generators to simulate these experiments, and record the momenta information of 
               \begin{document}$ \bar{p} $\end{document}
            , 
               \begin{document}$ \bar{n} $\end{document}
             that are possible to form a 
               \begin{document}$ \overline{\mathrm{D}} $\end{document}
            . We select the 
               \begin{document}$ \bar{p} $\end{document}
             and 
               \begin{document}$ \bar{n} $\end{document}
             according to a sufficiently large coalescence momentum 
               \begin{document}$ p_{0,\text{max}} $\end{document}
             (600 MeV for 
               \begin{document}$ \overline{\mathrm{D}} $\end{document}
            , 1 GeV for 
               \begin{document}$ \overline{\mathrm{He}} $\end{document}
            ), and then calculate the spectra of 
               \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
             for different 
               \begin{document}$  p_0^{ \overline{\mathrm{D}}} $\end{document}
             values that are smaller than 
               \begin{document}$ p_{0,\text{max}} $\end{document}
            . The 
               \begin{document}$ B_2 $\end{document}
             values are calculated by using Eq. (4), and we perform a 
               \begin{document}$ \chi^2 $\end{document}
             analysis to find the value of 
               \begin{document}$  p_0^{ \overline{\mathrm{D}}} $\end{document}
            . The best-fit 
               \begin{document}$ B_2 $\end{document}
             values are shown in Fig. 1. We find 
               \begin{document}$ \chi^2_{\text{min}}/{d.o.f}< 1 $\end{document}
             for all these fits, which means the fitting results are in good agreement with the experimental data. As shown by the figure, the 
               \begin{document}$ p_T $\end{document}
            -dependences are reproduced well by the coalescence model and the MC generators.

