sec.p:
By using PYTHIA to fit the 
               \begin{document}$ B_2 = 3.3\pm1.0\pm0.8\times10^{-3} $\end{document}
             data from the ALEPH 
               \begin{document}$ e^+e^-\rightarrow Z^0 \rightarrow \overline{\mathrm{D}} $\end{document}
             experiment [29], we find 
               \begin{document}$ p_0^{\overline{\mathrm{D}}}(Z^0) = 190^{+23}_{-27} $\end{document}
             MeV. Considering the similarity between the dynamics of the 
               \begin{document}$ Z^0 $\end{document}
             decay and DM annihilation, we set 
               \begin{document}$ p_0^{\overline{\mathrm{D}}}(Z^0) $\end{document}
             to be the coalescence momentum for the DM annihilation process 
               \begin{document}$ \chi\chi \rightarrow \overline{\mathrm{D}} + X $\end{document}
            .

For 
               \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
            , we adopt the 
               \begin{document}$ p_0^{\overline{\mathrm{He}}} $\end{document}
             value obtained in our previous work [22], which determining 
               \begin{document}$ p_0^{\overline{\mathrm{He}}} $\end{document}
             by fitting the ALICE 
               \begin{document}$ \sqrt{s} = 7 $\end{document}
             TeV 
               \begin{document}$ pp $\end{document}
            -collision data. The results are listed in Table 2. Note that 
               \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
             particles can be produced from two channels: direct formation from the coalescence of 
               \begin{document}$ \bar{p}\bar{p}\bar{n} $\end{document}
            , or through the 
               \begin{document}$ \beta $\end{document}
            -decay of an antitriton 
               \begin{document}$ \overline{\text{T}} $\end{document}
             (
               \begin{document}$ \bar{p}\bar{n}\bar{n} $\end{document}
            ). The direct formation channel is suppressed by the Coulomb repulsion between the two antiprotons, so some previous works only considered the antitriton channel. However, our calculation shows that the direct formation channel is not negligible. The coalescence momentum of 
               \begin{document}$ ^3\overline{\mathrm{He}} $\end{document}
             is only slightly smaller than that of 
               \begin{document}$ \overline{\text{T}} $\end{document}
            , and the Gamow factor 
               \begin{document}$ \mathcal{G}\sim \exp(-2\pi\alpha m_p/p_0^{\overline{\mathrm{He}}}) \approx 0.8 $\end{document}
             [38], which indicates that the Coulomb repulsion may not be significant. From these facts, it is reasonable to ignore the Coulomb repulsion in the MC simulation, and the contributions from both channels are included in this work. Our MC calculation shows that about 30% of 
               \begin{document}$ ^3\overline{\mathrm{He}} $\end{document}
             is produced through the direct formation channel. Due to the lack of 
               \begin{document}$ e^+e^-\rightarrow  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
             experiment data, we set 
               \begin{document}$ p_0^{\overline{\mathrm{He}}/\overline{\mathrm{T}}}(\texttt{PYTHIA)} $\end{document}
             to be the coalescence momentum for the DM annihilation process 
               \begin{document}$ \chi\chi \rightarrow \overline{\mathrm{He}}/\overline{\mathrm{T}} + X $\end{document}
            . It is known that the coalescence momentum varies for different processes and center-of-mass energies [39], and the relation 
               \begin{document}$ B_A\approx p_0^{3(A-1)} $\end{document}
             makes 
               \begin{document}$ p_0 $\end{document}
             a crucial factor for the uncertainties of the final fluxes. In some previous analyses, the value of 
               \begin{document}$ p_0^{\overline{\mathrm{He}}} $\end{document}
             was estimated using various approaches, for example by using the binding energy relation between 
               \begin{document}$ p_0^{\overline{\mathrm{He}}} $\end{document}
             and 
               \begin{document}$ p_0^{\overline{\mathrm{D}}} $\end{document}
            , or assuming the ratio 
               \begin{document}$ p_0^{\overline{\mathrm{He}}}/p_0^{\overline{\mathrm{D}}} = p_0^{\mathrm{He}}/p_0^{\mathrm{D}} $\end{document}
             [17], and some works just set 
               \begin{document}$ p_0^{\overline{\mathrm{He}}} = p_0^{\overline{\mathrm{D}}} $\end{document}
              [18]. The 
               \begin{document}$ p_0^{\overline{\mathrm{He}}} $\end{document}
             results from these approaches are different. It is worth mentioning that our 
               \begin{document}$ p_0^{\overline{\mathrm{He}}} $\end{document}
             value is relatively small compared to previous works, which leads to conservative DM contributions.

