sec.p:
For the primary anti-particles originating from DM annihilations, the injection spectra are calculated using PYTHIA 8.2. We simulate the annihilation of Majorana DM particles by a positron-electron annihilation process 
               \begin{document}$ e^+e^- \rightarrow \phi^* \rightarrow f\bar{f} $\end{document}
            , where 
               \begin{document}$ \phi^* $\end{document}
             is a fictitious scaler singlet and f is a standard model final state. We set 
               \begin{document}$ \sqrt{s} = 2m_{\chi} $\end{document}
             and switch off all initial-state-radiations in PYTHIA 8.2, to mimic the dynamics of DM annihilation. Three kinds of final state are considered: 
               \begin{document}$ q\bar{q} $\end{document}
             (q stands for u or d quark), 
               \begin{document}$ b\bar{b} $\end{document}
             and 
               \begin{document}$ W^+W^- $\end{document}
            . In the EPOS-LHC and DPMJET-III generators, only hadrons can be set as the initial states, which does not resemble the properties of DM annihilations.

For the secondary anti-particles produced in 
               \begin{document}$ pp$\end{document}
            -collisions, EPOS-LHC and DPMJET-III are used to generate the energy spectra. The default parameters in PYTHIA 8.2 (the Monash tune [40]) are focused to reproduce the experimental results at high center-of-mass energies (like ATLAS at 
               \begin{document}$ \sqrt{s} = 7 $\end{document}
             TeV [41]), but are not optimized for energy regions around a few tens of GeV, which give the dominating contributions for secondary CR anti-particles. To evaluate the performance of MC generators at low center-of-mass energies, we compare the 
               \begin{document}$ \bar{p} $\end{document}
             differential invariant cross-section obtained by MC generators and the NA49 data at 
               \begin{document}$ \sqrt{s} = 17.3 $\end{document}
             GeV [42]. This comparison shows that EPOS-LHC has the best performance, and DPMJET-III is also in relatively good agreement with experiment, while the production cross-section of 
               \begin{document}$ \bar{p} $\end{document}
             given by PYTHIA 8.2 is larger than the NA49 data by roughly a factor of two. In this paper, we will draw our conclusion based on the results from EPOS-LHC, and the difference between EPOS-LHC and DPMJET-III can be used as a rough estimation of the uncertainties from different MC generators.

The propagation of charged CR particles is assumed to be random diffusions in a cylindrical diffusion halo with radius 
               \begin{document}$ r_h \approx 20 $\end{document}
             kpc and half-height 
               \begin{document}$ z_h = 1 \sim 10 $\end{document}
             kpc. The diffusion equation is written as [43, 44]:

where 
               \begin{document}$  f(\vec{r},p,t) $\end{document}
             is the number density in phase spaces at the particle momentum p and position 
               \begin{document}$ \vec{r} $\end{document}
            , and 
               \begin{document}$ q(\vec{r},p) $\end{document}
             is the source term. 
               \begin{document}$ D_{xx} $\end{document}
             is the spatial diffusion coefficient, which is parameterized as 
               \begin{document}$ D_{xx} = \beta D_0 (R/R_0)^{\delta} $\end{document}
            , where 
               \begin{document}$ R = p/(Ze) $\end{document}
             is the rigidity of the CR particle with electric charge 
               \begin{document}$ Ze $\end{document}
            , 
               \begin{document}$ \delta $\end{document}
             is the spectral power index, which takes two different values 
               \begin{document}$ \delta = \delta_{1(2)} $\end{document}
             when R is below (above) a reference rigidity 
               \begin{document}$ R_0 $\end{document}
            , 
               \begin{document}$ D_0 $\end{document}
             is a constant normalization coefficient, and 
               \begin{document}$ \beta = v/c $\end{document}
             is the velocity of CR particles. 
               \begin{document}$ \vec{V}_c $\end{document}
             quantifies the velocity of the galactic wind convection. The diffusive re-acceleration is described as diffusions in the momentum space, which is described by the parameter 
               \begin{document}$ D_{pp} = p^2V_a^2/(9D_{xx}) $\end{document}
            , where 
               \begin{document}$ V_a $\end{document}
             is the Alfvén velocity that characterizes the propagation of weak disturbances in a magnetic field. 
               \begin{document}$ \dot{p} \equiv {\rm d}p/{\rm d}t $\end{document}
             is the momentum loss rate, and 
               \begin{document}$ \tau_f $\end{document}
             and 
               \begin{document}$ \tau_r $\end{document}
             are the timescales of particle fragmentation and radioactive decay respectively. For boundary conditions, we assume that the number densities of CR particles vanish at the boundary of the halo: 
               \begin{document}$  f(r_h,z,p) = f(r,\pm z_h, p) = 0 $\end{document}
            . The steady-state diffusion condition is achieved by setting 
               \begin{document}$ \partial f/\partial t = 0 $\end{document}
            . We numerically solve the diffusion equation Eq. (5) by using the GALPROP v54 code [45-49]. The primary CR nucleus injection spectra are assumed to have a broken power law behavior 
               \begin{document}$ f_p(\vec{r},p)\propto p^{\gamma_p} $\end{document}
            , with the injection index 
               \begin{document}$ \gamma_p = $\end{document}


               \begin{document}$ \gamma_{p1} (\gamma_{p2}) $\end{document}
             for the nucleus rigidity 
               \begin{document}$ R_p $\end{document}
             below (above) a reference value 
               \begin{document}$ R_{ps} $\end{document}
            . The spatial distribution of the interstellar gas and the primary sources of CR nuclei are taken from Ref. [45].

The injection of CR particles is described by the source term in the diffusion equation. For the primary CR antiparticles 
