Values of the main parameters in the “MIN”, “MED” and “MAX” models, derived from fitting to the AMS-02 
                        \begin{document}$ B/C $\end{document}
                      and proton data based on the GALPROP code [57]. The parameter 
                        \begin{document}$ D_0 $\end{document}
                      is in units of 
                        \begin{document}$ 10^{28}\; \mathrm{cm}^2\cdot\mathrm{s}^{-1} $\end{document}
                     .

sec.p:
The 95% CL upper limits of DM annihilation cross-sections are derived by performing a frequentist 
                  \begin{document}$ \chi^2- $\end{document}
               analysis, with 
                  \begin{document}$ \chi^2 $\end{document}
                defined as:

where 
                  \begin{document}$ f^{\mathrm{exp}}_i $\end{document}
                is the central value of the experimental 
                  \begin{document}$ \bar{p}/p $\end{document}
                ratio, 
                  \begin{document}$ \sigma_i $\end{document}
                is the data error, 
                  \begin{document}$ f^{\mathrm{exp}}_i $\end{document}
                is the theoretical prediction of 
                  \begin{document}$ \bar{p}/p $\end{document}
               , and i denotes the 
                  \begin{document}$ i- $\end{document}
               th data point. For the 95% CL upper limits of 
                  \begin{document}$ \bar{p}/p $\end{document}
                given by the HAWC experiment, we set 
                  \begin{document}$ f^{\mathrm{exp}}_i = 0 $\end{document}
               , and the value of the upper limit corresponds to 
                  \begin{document}$ 1.96\sigma_i $\end{document}
               . For a specific DM mass, we first calculate the minimal value of 
                  \begin{document}$ \chi^2 $\end{document}
               , and then the 95% CL upper limits on DM annihilation cross-sections corresponding to 
                  \begin{document}$ \Delta\chi^2 = 3.84 $\end{document}
                for one parameter. See Ref. [13] for more details. The upper limits for different annihilation channels are shown in Fig. 3, with the production cross-section of secondary 
                  \begin{document}$ \bar{p} $\end{document}
                generated by EPOS-LHC. We can see that the differences between the upper limits for various propagation models and DM profiles can reach one to two orders of magnitude. As shown in previous works [17, 58], the final flux uncertainties from propagation models and DM profiles can be larger than one order of magnitude. However, if we use these cross-section upper limits to constrain the maximal flux of 
                  \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
                and 
                  \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
               , the final uncertainties from the propagation model and the DM profile can be reduced to merely 30% [22]. Comparisons of the maximal 
                  \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
                fluxes in different propagation models and DM profiles are shown in Fig. 4. It can be seen that the uncertainties are small.

