sec.title:
Constraints from HESS galactic center 
                  \begin{document}$ \gamma $\end{document}
               -ray data

sec.p:
The galactic center (GC) is a promising place for detecting DM interactions, because of the expected high DM density. The 10-year HESS 
                  \begin{document}$ \gamma $\end{document}
               -ray data [34] focus on a small area around the galactic center, and constrains the DM annihilation cross-sections well for “Cuspy” type DM profiles, which have a large gradient at the inner galactic halo. These include the "Einasto" profile and the "NFW" profile. For DM mass 
                  \begin{document}$ m_{\chi} \gtrsim 1 $\end{document}
                TeV, the galactic center 
                  \begin{document}$ \gamma $\end{document}
               -ray can place more stringent upper limits than the 
                  \begin{document}$ \bar{p}/p $\end{document}
                data. However, for “Cored” type DM profiles, which are flat near the galactic center, such as the "Isothermal" profile, the constraints from the 
                  \begin{document}$ \gamma $\end{document}
               -ray data are relatively weak.

The latest galactic center 
                  \begin{document}$ \gamma $\end{document}
               -ray analysis, with 254 hours' exposure, was published in 2016 by HESS [34]. The upper limits are calculated for several DM profiles and DM annihilation channels, but the 
                  \begin{document}$ \gamma $\end{document}
               -ray flux data have not been publicly released. Since the relative statistical error of a data point is inversely proportional to the square root of the number of counts in the bins, we can approximately estimate the 254-hour results by rescaling previous HESS 
                  \begin{document}$ \gamma $\end{document}
               -ray data [33], which were published in 2011 and for which exposure time was 112 hours. To obtain the upper limits for other DM profiles and channels, we perform a 
                  \begin{document}$ \chi^2 $\end{document}
                analysis to the 112-hour 
                  \begin{document}$ \gamma $\end{document}
               -ray flux data and estimate the 254-hour results by rescaling the data errors by a factor 
                  \begin{document}$ \sqrt{112/254} $\end{document}
               . The flux residual is defined as 
                  \begin{document}$ R^{\mathrm{exp}} =   F^{\mathrm{exp}}_{\mathrm{Sr}}-F^{\mathrm{exp}}_{\mathrm{Bg}} $\end{document}
               , where 
                  \begin{document}$ F^{\mathrm{exp}}_{\mathrm{Sr}} $\end{document}
                and 
                  \begin{document}$ F^{\mathrm{exp}}_{\mathrm{Bg}} $\end{document}
                are the experimental 
                  \begin{document}$ \gamma $\end{document}
               -ray flux data from the source region and from the background region respectively, and the error of 
                  \begin{document}$ R^{\mathrm{exp}} $\end{document}
                is provided in Ref. [33]. 
                  \begin{document}$ R^{\mathrm{th}} = F^{\mathrm{th}}_{\mathrm{Sr}}-F^{\mathrm{th}}_{\mathrm{Bg}} $\end{document}
                is the theoretical value of the flux residual, and the differential flux 
                  \begin{document}$ F^{\mathrm{th}} $\end{document}
                is calculated by the following formula:

where 
                  \begin{document}$ \mathrm{d} N_{\gamma}/\mathrm{d}E_{\gamma} $\end{document}
                is the energy spectrum of photons produced in one DM annihilation, and 
                  \begin{document}$ \Omega $\end{document}
                is the total spherical angle of the source or background regions. We adopt the reflected background technique described in Ref. [33] to determine the source region and background regions, and calculate the flux residual to perform the 
                  \begin{document}$ \chi^2 $\end{document}
                analysis. We randomly choose 540 pointing positions near the GC, with the maximal distance between the pointing position and the GC being 
                  \begin{document}$ 1.5^{\circ} $\end{document}
               . We first calculate the minimal 
                  \begin{document}$ \chi^2 $\end{document}
                value, and then the 95% CL upper limit corresponds to 
                  \begin{document}$ \Delta\chi^2 = 3.84 $\end{document}
               . The results are shown in Fig. 5. We can see that there are large gaps between the upper limits for different DM profiles. As expected, the constraints are stringent for DM profiles that are cuspy at the GC, but for a cored one like the Isothermal profile, the limits are rather weak. For various DM profiles, the constraints from 
                  \begin{document}$ \bar{p}/p $\end{document}
                data are are similar, because the DM densities in the diffusion halo are similar in different DM profiles, except for the GC region. However, for 
                  \begin{document}$ \gamma $\end{document}
               -ray data, the GC region provides the most stringent constraints for heavy DM particles, which leads to the large gaps between DM profiles.

