It is worth mentioning that the Fermi-LAT experiment [59] also collected a large amount of 
                  \begin{document}$ \gamma $\end{document}
               -ray data near the GC, and the relatively large region of interest can reduce the large gaps between different DM profiles. However, the energy range of Fermi-LAT observations (from 20 MeV to more than 300 GeV) is much lower than that of HESS, and thus provides a weaker limitation on large DM mass. For example, the analysis in Ref. [60] shows that for a steep profile like “NFW”, HESS gives stronger constraints than Fermi-LAT at 
                  \begin{document}$ E\gtrsim1 $\end{document}
                TeV. For a flat profile like “Isothermal”, the Fermi-LAT limits derived in Ref. [61] are slightly weaker than the 
                  \begin{document}$ \bar{p}/p $\end{document}
                constraints at 
                  \begin{document}$ E\approx 10 $\end{document}
                TeV. From these facts, to make the most conservative conclusion, we use the 
                  \begin{document}$ \bar{p}/p $\end{document}
                limits to calculate the maximal 
                  \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
                and 
                  \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
                fluxes in the “Isothermal” profile, and use the HESS 
                  \begin{document}$ \gamma $\end{document}
               -ray limits for the “Einasto” profile in the following sections.

sec.title:

  \begin{document}$ \overline{\mathrm{D}} $\end{document}
AND 
  \begin{document}$ \overline{\mathrm{He}} $\end{document}
FLUX FOR LARGE DM MASS

sec.p:
With the DM annihilation cross-section upper limits to hand, we can derive the maximal 
                  \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
                and 
                  \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
                fluxes for different annihilation channels, propagation models, and DM profiles. As shown in Fig. 4, by constraining the DM annihilation cross-section with the 
                  \begin{document}$ \bar{p}/p $\end{document}
                data, the uncertainties from the propagation models are small. We thus present our results for the “MED” propagation model, and other models do not affect our conclusions. For illustrative purposes, the particle mass of the heavy DM is set to be 
                  \begin{document}$ m_{\chi} = 10 $\end{document}
                and 50 TeV, which is smaller than the unitarity bound for a self-conjugate DM [62]. However, it is worth mentioning that our analysis is largely model-independent, and we do not assume that DM has thermal origins.

Currently, the AMS-02 detector has the strongest detection ability for both 
                  \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
                and 
                  \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
               . For the 
                  \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
                flux, the AMS-02 detection sensitivity is given in Ref. [39], while the sensitivity for 
                  \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
                has only been released in terms of the 
                  \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}}/\mathrm{He} $\end{document}
                ratio in Ref. [20]. To study the detection prospects of AMS-02, we present our results in terms of 
                  \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
                fluxes and 
                  \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}}/\mathrm{He} $\end{document}
                ratios.

The results for the “Isothermal” profile with 
                  \begin{document}$ m_{\chi} = 10 $\end{document}
                and 50 TeV are presented in Fig. 7, with the DM annihilation cross-section constrained by the AMS-02 and HAWC 
                  \begin{document}$ \bar{p}/p $\end{document}
                data. The top three figures show the results for 
                  \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
                fluxes for different annihilation channels, while the bottom three figures present the 
                  \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}}/\mathrm{He} $\end{document}
                ratio results. The blue shaded areas represent the prospective AMS-02 detection sensitivity after 18 years of data collection, and the error bands show the uncertainties from coalescence momenta. Note that for 
                  \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
               , the error bands for the secondary background are thinner than the line width. We can see that for 
                  \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
               , the DM contributions exceed the secondary backgrounds in the energy region 
                  \begin{document}$ T/A\gtrsim300 $\end{document}
                GeV. For 
                  \begin{document}$ b\bar{b} $\end{document}
                and 
                  \begin{document}$ W^+W^- $\end{document}
                channels and 
                  \begin{document}$ m_{\chi} = 50 $\end{document}
                TeV, the excess can be as large as one order of magnitude. Similarly, for 
                  \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
               , the excess exists at a kinetic energy of around 800 GeV per nucleon, and the primary 
                  \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
                fluxes originating from DM annihilation can be 20 times larger than the secondary background with 
                  \begin{document}$ m_{\chi} = 50 $\end{document}
                TeV. Despite the fluxes of these anti-nuclei being small at high kinetic energies, and far below the AMS-02 sensitivities, these excesses can be promising windows for future detections.

