sec.p:
We also consider the process 
                  \begin{document}$ \chi\chi \rightarrow \phi\phi \rightarrow f\bar{f}f\bar{f} $\end{document}
               , where two DM particles first annihilate into a couple of mediators, and then the mediators decay into standard model final states. If the mass of the mediator is much smaller than that of the DM particle, the mediator will be highly boosted. The 
                  \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
                and 
                  \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
                produced in this process are thus expected to assemble in high energy regions, which provides a high signal-to-background ratio for the high energy window.

By following the steps described in Sec. IV, we obtain the 95% CL upper limit of cross-sections for the annihilation process with mediators. The results for mediator mass 
                  \begin{document}$ m_{\phi} = 200 $\end{document}
                GeV are presented in Fig. 9. Similar to the results for direct annihilations, for the “Isothermal” profile, the most stringent constraints are from 
                  \begin{document}$ \bar{p}/p $\end{document}
                data, while for the “Einasto” profile, the 
                  \begin{document}$ \gamma $\end{document}
               -ray limitations are stricter. Again, we use the AMS-02 and HAWC 
                  \begin{document}$ \bar{p}/p $\end{document}
                data to constrain the “Isothermal” profile, and the “Einasto” profile is restricted by the HESS GC 
                  \begin{document}$ \gamma $\end{document}
               -ray data.

