The results for the “Isothermal” profile and “Einasto” profile with 
                  \begin{document}$ m_{\phi} = 200 $\end{document}
                GeV are presented in Fig. 10 and Fig. 11 respectively. As expected, the DM contributions are boosted to high energy regions, and we get similar conclusions as in the direct annihilation channels. For the “Isothermal” profile with 
                  \begin{document}$ m_{\chi} = 50 $\end{document}
                TeV, the high energy window opens for both 
                  \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
                and 
                  \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
                in all decay channels, especially for 
                  \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
               , where the excesses can reach two orders of magnitude in the 
                  \begin{document}$ q\bar{q} $\end{document}
                and 
                  \begin{document}$ b\bar{b} $\end{document}
                channels. For 
                  \begin{document}$ m_{\chi} = 10 $\end{document}
                TeV, the DM contributions for 
                  \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
                and 
                  \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
                are comparable to the secondary backgrounds.

