sec.p:
However, as shown in Fig. 11, for the “Einasto” profile, the excesses in high energy regions disappear for 
                  \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
                for all DM masses and mediator decay channels. For 
                  \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
               , the contributions from DM with 
                  \begin{document}$ m_{\chi} = 50 $\end{document}
                TeV can be larger than the background calculated by using DPMJET-III. For EPOS-LHC, however, the only excess appears in the 
                  \begin{document}$ q\bar{q} $\end{document}
                decay channel with 
                  \begin{document}$ m_{\chi} = 50 $\end{document}
                TeV.

For other mediator masses, we reach the same conclusion. Taking the 
                  \begin{document}$ \chi\chi \rightarrow \phi\phi \rightarrow 4q $\end{document}
                channel as an example, we calculate the 
                  \begin{document}$  \overline{\text{D}} $\end{document}
                fluxes and 
                  \begin{document}$  ^3\overline{\text{He}} $\end{document}
                ratios for mediator mass 
                  \begin{document}$ m_{\phi} = 60 $\end{document}
               , 200 and 600 GeV, and present the results for the “Isothermal” profile in Fig. 12. It can be seen that with the growth of the mediator mass, the DM contributions in low energy regions increase significantly. However, in high energy regions, in which we are interested, the variations of the results are small.

